1
00:00:00,292 --> 00:00:05,777
I know everyone wants me to say "Devil Wears Prada" line because it's the one that's quoted to me most.

2
00:00:05,777 --> 00:00:09,164
Clearly the one that's quoted to me most will be a "Devil Wears Prada" line.

3
00:00:09,164 --> 00:00:10,485
Something about cheese.

4
00:00:10,485 --> 00:00:19,777
Exactly. Something about cheese.

5
00:00:19,777 --> 00:00:22,521
Emily, what is the one activity you do every day?&nbsp;

6
00:00:22,521 --> 00:00:25,903
I wish I did transcendental meditation every day.

7
00:00:25,903 --> 00:00:27,848
I don't do it every day.

8
00:00:27,848 --> 00:00:32,498
I do eat dark chocolate every day, so I'm gonna do that.

9
00:00:32,498 --> 00:00:35,799
—In high school, you turn out a pop record contract? —Yes.

10
00:00:35,799 --> 00:00:42,248
Who is the one collaborator that could take you out of your pop retirement?

11
00:00:42,248 --> 00:00:49,322
Can he just prize me out of this pop reclusivity?

12
00:00:49,322 --> 00:00:53,081
I think if anyone can, it's Lin.

13
00:00:53,081 --> 00:00:56,238
Is there one song of his that you wish you collaborated with him on?

14
00:00:56,238 --> 00:01:06,913
Well, my kids always say I'm not allowed to play it, but it's "Dear Theodosia" 'cause it's just the most beautiful lullaby on earth.

15
00:01:06,913 --> 00:01:10,169
Every time I play it in the car, the kids are like, "It's too sad."

16
00:01:10,169 --> 00:01:12,097
It's devastating.

17
00:01:12,097 --> 00:01:15,252
What is the one relationship that taught you the most about who you are?

18
00:01:15,252 --> 00:01:18,157
Sorry, John Krasinski, but it is our children.

19
00:01:18,157 --> 00:01:25,659
Because you do go through this complete awakening when you have kids.

20
00:01:25,659 --> 00:01:28,281
I know any parent will attest.

21
00:01:28,281 --> 00:01:38,603
The challenge of it, the beauty of it, that's sort of reclamation of maybe who you really are.

22
00:01:38,603 --> 00:01:44,362
And how I don't think anybody sees you as purely as your children do.

23
00:01:44,362 --> 00:01:47,303
Or bringing you back to earth like they do.

24
00:01:47,303 --> 00:01:54,010
I find that like the most kaleidoscopic experience of my life.

25
00:01:54,010 --> 00:01:56,887
What is the one parenting hot take you stand by?

26
00:01:56,887 --> 00:02:03,097
Bribery. Isn't that half of parenting?

27
00:02:03,097 --> 00:02:04,735
What do you bribe them with?

28
00:02:04,735 --> 00:02:10,573
I mean, definitely, their love of dark chocolate is matched with my own.&nbsp;

29
00:02:10,573 --> 00:02:16,202
If you eat another piece of broccoli, you could get another square of chocolate.

30
00:02:16,202 --> 00:02:19,234
What is the one quality you look for in a mom friend?

31
00:02:19,234 --> 00:02:24,151
I have friends where there's just this secret language of understanding.

32
00:02:24,151 --> 00:02:25,847
And yeah, I look for that.

33
00:02:25,847 --> 00:02:31,773
That sort of effortless secret language that you have with some other moms that just get it in every way.

34
00:02:31,773 --> 00:02:33,759
Not just moms, just friends in general.

35
00:02:33,759 --> 00:02:41,366
Your husband, John Krasinski, directed "A Quiet Place" which you also starred in.

36
00:02:41,366 --> 00:02:47,256
What is the one drive to or from work that you'll never forget?

37
00:02:47,256 --> 00:02:55,497
I think he will never forget the first day when I'd left it rather till the last minute to go, "Do you know how to shoot a film?"

38
00:02:55,497 --> 00:03:01,339
Because I don't know how to shoot a film, so I'm just wondering if you know what you're doing.

39
00:03:01,339 --> 00:03:06,389
And then actually the drive home was clearly like I'd had an awakening.

40
00:03:06,389 --> 00:03:12,639
Seeing that this person who I thought I knew everything about had this sort of secret power.

41
00:03:12,639 --> 00:03:23,599
It was really amazing seeing this whole other superpower that he had that I don't think he even knew what he was capable of doing.

42
00:03:23,599 --> 00:03:26,310
What's the one movie you can quote embarrassingly well?

43
00:03:26,310 --> 00:03:32,340
It's only because I just showed it to my kids recently.

44
00:03:32,340 --> 00:03:35,600
I love that bit. She's so brilliant, isn't it?

45
00:03:35,600 --> 00:03:39,211
What is the one audition that changed the trajectory of your career?

46
00:03:39,211 --> 00:03:51,458
It would have to be for "The Devil Wears Prada."

47
00:03:51,458 --> 00:04:04,785
I was 22 and I was actually auditioning at Fox Studios for another movie that thank God I didn't get.

48
00:04:04,785 --> 00:04:09,652
And they said, "Hey, while you are here, do you want to audition for "The Devil Wears Prada"?

49
00:04:09,652 --> 00:04:13,891
And that changed my life completely in every way.

50
00:04:13,891 --> 00:04:16,480
And now you're returning to "The Devil Wears Prada."

51
00:04:16,480 --> 00:04:17,651
Years later.

52
00:04:17,651 --> 00:04:22,720
Am I having a hallucination?

53
00:04:22,720 --> 00:04:25,537
We were at runway at the same time, Miranda.

54
00:04:25,537 --> 00:04:31,240
What is the one shift in dynamics on set that's been the most fun to experience?

55
00:04:31,240 --> 00:04:35,189
Maybe we're just even less tolerant of wearing high heels all day.

56
00:04:35,189 --> 00:04:41,151
Maybe we just complain more.

57
00:04:41,151 --> 00:04:44,572
I know 20 years has gone by.

58
00:04:44,572 --> 00:04:46,724
But it felt like a blink.

59
00:04:46,724 --> 00:04:51,720
It felt like nothing and so much has happened in between.

60
00:04:51,720 --> 00:04:59,721
Stanley Tucci is now my brother-in-law and we are family in every single way.&nbsp;

61
00:04:59,721 --> 00:05:03,598
He would've been my chosen family and now he actually is my family.

62
00:05:03,598 --> 00:05:04,839
Does that show up on set?

63
00:05:04,839 --> 00:05:11,115
Yeah, he told me that I was shameless most of the time with some of my comedy choices.

64
00:05:11,115 --> 00:05:14,346
They would call "Cut" and he'd just go, "Oh shameless."

65
00:05:14,346 --> 00:05:18,976
What is the one piece of advice from Meryl Streep that you still hear in your head?

66
00:05:18,976 --> 00:05:21,355
She doesn't give out advice.

67
00:05:21,355 --> 00:05:25,601
She doesn't feel like she wants to impart wisdom on you.

68
00:05:25,601 --> 00:05:28,961
She wants to be one of the peeps, you know?

69
00:05:28,961 --> 00:05:31,093
I would love her to give me advice.

70
00:05:31,093 --> 00:05:33,865
I don't think she would presume to.

71
00:05:33,865 --> 00:05:38,351
What is the one line from your career that you find most iconic?

72
00:05:38,351 --> 00:05:44,921
I know everyone wants me to say a "Devil Wears Prada" line because it's the one that's quoted to me most.

73
00:05:44,921 --> 00:05:55,520
But there's a moment in "Oppenheimer" where Kitty Oppenheimer has been obviously drinking heavily and just deteriorating as a character.

74
00:05:55,520 --> 00:05:58,307
And becoming more volatile and unreliable.

75
00:05:58,307 --> 00:06:00,812
And no one wants her to testify.

76
00:06:00,812 --> 00:06:05,447
And so the odds are kind of stacked against her and she's super wobbly.

77
00:06:05,447 --> 00:06:10,962
And then she just finally gathers it and she goes, "Well, it was also very long ago, Mr. Rob, wasn't it?"

78
00:06:10,962 --> 00:06:14,390
Long enough to have forgotten and she kind of comes back to life.

79
00:06:14,390 --> 00:06:22,195
Even on the day, I remember Chris Nolan saying, "Don't be afraid to just stick that landing with that line."

80
00:06:22,195 --> 00:06:24,720
Like don't be afraid of it just being a real moment.

81
00:06:24,720 --> 00:06:34,362
Clearly the one that's quoted to me most will be a "Devil Wears Prada" line.

82
00:06:34,362 --> 00:06:37,421
You are in Steven Spielberg's new sci-fi movie "Disclosure Day."

83
00:06:37,421 --> 00:06:41,534
Whatever happens, don't you let it go.

84
00:06:41,534 --> 00:06:43,970
What's the one surprise on Spielberg sets?

85
00:06:43,970 --> 00:06:46,603
How fun it was.

86
00:06:46,603 --> 00:06:49,513
He is so available as a person.

87
00:06:49,513 --> 00:06:56,126
Even if you want to dork out and ask him endless stories about "ET" or "Indiana Jones."

88
00:06:56,126 --> 00:07:02,081
He's just available and joyous and buoyant to be around.

89
00:07:02,081 --> 00:07:07,879
I was really amazed by the spontaneity of him.

90
00:07:07,879 --> 00:07:10,405
He doesn't pre-plan anything.

91
00:07:10,405 --> 00:07:11,661
Nothing's mapped out.

92
00:07:11,661 --> 00:07:14,322
He gets there, he feels it, and he's just...

93
00:07:14,322 --> 00:07:19,359
It was such a vibrant experience watching him work.

94
00:07:19,359 --> 00:07:26,558
You see why he's the greatest of all time.

95
00:07:26,558 --> 00:07:31,050
Yet he doesn't wear that like as his front foot.

96
00:07:31,050 --> 00:07:39,089
He's just a kid wanting to tell stories and wanting to bring you into the fold of it in every way.

97
00:07:39,089 --> 00:07:42,834
We were kind of bereft when that film ended.

98
00:07:42,834 --> 00:07:46,138
I felt like I needed to stare at a wall for a day.

99
00:07:46,138 --> 00:07:51,699
What is the one red flag you never ignore professionally or personally?

100
00:07:51,699 --> 00:07:53,374
Bad manners.

101
00:07:53,374 --> 00:07:55,844
Also, your instinct on someone.

102
00:07:55,844 --> 00:07:58,593
If something stinks, it's 'cause it stinks.

103
00:07:58,593 --> 00:08:05,688
I used to try to sort of get past that first instinct.

104
00:08:05,688 --> 00:08:12,878
If you felt a bit wobbly about someone or about a project, I'd always be like, "No, no, it'll be fine. I'm sure it'll be fine."

105
00:08:12,878 --> 00:08:18,828
I think you have to listen to that 'cause it's so loud if you listen to it.

106
00:08:18,828 --> 00:08:21,500
What is the one insight you'd give your younger self?

107
00:08:21,500 --> 00:08:25,102
Don't sweat the small stuff.

108
00:08:25,102 --> 00:08:27,602
If you're not losing sleep over it, don't worry about it.

